{
    "title": "The Pioneer Circle",
    "description": "Meet the pioneers who established the foundations of VR: Jaron Lanier, Brenda Laurel, and Myron Krueger.",
    "theme": {
        "primaryColor": "#5900ff",
        "fontBody": "Rajdhani, sans-serif"
    },
    "modules": [
        {
            "id": "pioneers_pd_2.2",
            "title": "Establishing the Foundations",
            "type": "progressive-disclosure",
            "content": {
                "sections": [
                    {
                        "title": "Jaron Lanier—Naming Virtual Reality",
                        "media": {
                            "type": "image",
                            "src": "../assets/images/module2/lanier_dataglove.jpg",
                            "alt": "Jaron Lanier with DataGlove"
                        },
                        "mediaLayout": "left",
                        "content": "<p>In 1987, Jaron Lanier coined the term \"virtual reality\" and founded VPL Research. His systems cost hundreds of thousands of dollars, but he articulated a humanistic vision: \"Virtual reality is the first medium that doesn't narrow us. Instead, it expands what we can be.\" He saw VR as a consciousness expansion tool.</p>",
                        "triggerLabel": "Transformation"
                    },
                    {
                        "title": "Brenda Laurel—Transformation Through Technology",
                        "media": {
                            "type": "image",
                            "src": "../assets/images/module2/brenda_laurel.jpg",
                            "alt": "Brenda Laurel portrait"
                        },
                        "mediaLayout": "right",
                        "content": "<p>Brenda Laurel argued that human-computer interaction should create transformative experiences. In \"Computers as Theatre\" (1991), she wrote: \"The goal of interaction design should not just be usability, but the transformation of the user through the experience.\" This became core to cyberdelic practice.</p>",
                        "triggerLabel": "Artificial Reality"
                    },
                    {
                        "title": "Myron Krueger—Artificial Reality",
                        "content": "<p>Myron Krueger coined \"artificial reality\" for his VIDEOPLACE system (1974-1990). Users moved naturally in space while cameras tracked them. His insight: responsive environments can alter consciousness even without headsets. This influenced later cyberdelic design.</p>",
                        "triggerLabel": "The Gap"
                    },
                    {
                        "title": "The Gap They Couldn't Cross",
                        "content": "<p>These pioneers had grand visions, but 1980s-90s technology couldn't deliver. Headsets weighed pounds, resolution was poor, and systems cost over $100,000. The vision existed, the capability didn't.</p>",
                        "triggerLabel": "Legacy"
                    },
                    {
                        "title": "What They Established",
                        "content": "<p>Despite limitations, they established crucial foundations: VR as transformative space, embodied interaction, and presence as a psychological state. These insights became proven principles when hardware finally improved.</p>",
                        "triggerLabel": "Test Understanding"
                    }
                ]
            }
        },
